literature, culture, and history, which serve to erase or marginalize the colonial and postcolonial locations in which British national identity has been articulated. This volume breaks new ground by drawing together a range of disciplinary approaches in order to resituate the relationship between British national identity and Englishness within a global framework. Ranging from the literature and history of empire to analyses of contemporary culture, postcolonial writing, political rhetoric, and postimperial memory after 9/11, this collection demonstrates that far from being parochial or self-involved, the question of Englishness offers an important avenue for thinking about the politics of national identity in our postcolonial and globalized world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aImperialism. 0aNational characteristics, BritishxHistory. 0aNational characteristics, EnglishxHistory. 0aNationalismzGreat BritainxColoniesxHistory. 0aNationalismzGreat BritainxHistory. 0aPostcolonialismzGreat BritainxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aBickford-Smith, Vivian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aByrne, Bridget, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuffy, Enda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGhose, Sheila, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHart, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacPhee, Graham, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacPhee, Graham, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNash, Geoffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPoddar, Prem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/